ary on the Old Testament |volume=1 |year=1885 |publisher=T&T Clark |location=Edinburgh |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kissling |first=Paul |title=Genesis |publisher=College Press |year=2004 |volume=volume 1 |isbn= 9780899008752|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lotBnvqdmeQC&pg=PP4#v=onepage&q=In%20the%20beginning&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Kugle |first=James L. |title=Traditions of the Bible |publisher=Harvard University Press |year=1998 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QUkaVq_GlJUC&pg=PA222#v=onepage&q=%22Ham%20laughed%22&f=false |ref=harv|isbn=9780674791510 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Levenson |first=Jon D. |editor1-last=Berlin |editor1-first=Adele |editor2-last=Brettler |editor2-first=Marc Zvi |title=The Jewish study Bible |chapter=Genesis: Introduction and Annotations |year=2004 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195297515/page/26 26] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-529751-5 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aDuy3p5QvEYC#v=onepage&q&f=false |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195297515/page/26 }} ([https://books.google.com/books?id=aDuy3p5QvEYC&pg=PR5#v=snippet&q=Levenson&f=false Levenson author note]).\n*{{cite book |last=Lulat |first=G |title=A History of African Higher Education from Antiquity to the Present: A Critical Synthesis. |year=2005 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara |isbn=9780313068669 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J00xEkY-vTEC&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=misnomer%20ham&f=false |pages=85, 86 |ref=harv |quote=an ideologically driven misnomer...}}\n*{{cite book |last=Metcalf |first=Alida C. |title=Go-betweens and the Colonization of Brazil, 1500\u20131600 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lWuNIISvBqIC#v=snippet&q=ham%20curse&f=false |year=2005 |publisher=[[University of Texas Press]] |location=Austin |isbn=978-0292712768 |edition=1st |page=164 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Reeve|first1=W. Paul|title=Religion of a Different Color: Race and the Mormon Struggle for Whiteness|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=95j4BQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|location=New York, New York|isbn=978-0-19-975407-6}}\n*{{cite book |last=Robertson |first=John M. |authorlink= |title=Christianity and Mythology |year=1910 |publisher=Kessinger Publishing (2004 reprint) |location= |isbn=978-0-7661-8768-9 |pages=496 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=usGxKc9gMNwC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sadler |first=R.S. |authorlink= |title=Can a Cushite Change his Skin? |year=2005 |publisher=T&T Clark |location= |language= |isbn= 9780567029607|pages=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jNwI0AlRhuwC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sarna |first=Nahum |authorlink=Nahum Sarna |editor-last=Friedman |editor-first=Richard Elliott |title=The Creation of Sacred Literature: Composition and Redaction of the Biblical Text |chapter=The Anticipatory Use of Information as a Literary Feature of the Genesis Narratives |year=1981 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-09637-0 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HvjNTNWTyQUC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/creationofsacred0000unse }}\n*{{Cite book |last=Trost |first=Travis D. |title=Who should be king in Israel? |publisher=Peter Lang Publishing |year=2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FnvbpnRwxeYC&pg=PR6#v=onepage&q&f=false |ref=harv|isbn=9781433111518 }}\n*{{cite book |last=VanderKam |first=James Claire |authorlink=James VanderKam |chapter=The Righteousness of Noah |editor=John Joseph Collins |editor2=George W. E. Nickelsburg |title=Ideal figures in ancient Judaism: profiles and paradigms, Volumes 12\u201315 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Le4QAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=1 December 2013 |year=1980 |publisher=Scholars Press |location=Chico |isbn=978-0891304340 |pages=13\u201332|ref=harv}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150309230136/http://www3.nd.edu/~jvanderk/ VanderKam-Vitae]\n*{{cite book |last=Van Seters |first=John |editor1-last=VanderKam |editor1-first=James |title=From Revelation to Canon: Studies in the Hebrew Bible and Second Temple Literature |chapter=Geography as an evaluative tool |year=2000 |pages=|publisher=Brill |isbn= |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L352z_jZSmcC&pg=PA476#v=onepage&q=Putting%20them%20in%20their%20place%3A%20Geography%20as%20an%20evaluative%20tool&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Whitford |first=David M. |title=The curse of Ham in the Early Modern Era |publisher=Ashgate Publishing |year=2009 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hMb7_SL-OJYC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv|isbn=9780754666257 }}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Noah (Biblical figure)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/11571-noah \"Noah\"] from the 1901\u20131906 ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]''\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11088a.htm \"Noah\"]\u2014''[[Catholic Encyclopedia]]''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090711130618/http://muslimwiki.com/mw/index.php/Nuh \"Nuh\"]\u2014MuslimWiki\n\n{{Prophets of the Tanakh}}\n{{Adam to David}}\n{{Prophets in the Qur'an|no}}\n{{Noah's Ark}}\n{{Creationism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Noah| ]]\n[[Category:Bereshit (parsha)]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the Old Testament]]\n[[Category:Legendary progenitors]]\n[[Category:Longevity myths]]\n[[Category:Noach (parsha)| ]]\n[[Category:People celebrated in the Lutheran liturgical calendar]]\n[[Category:Book of Genesis people]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Noah (disambiguation)}}\n<!-- This article uses BC / AD dates. -->\n{{Infobox saint\n| name = Noah\n| image = NoahsSacrifice.JPG\n| imagesize = 250px\n| alt = \n| caption = ''Noah's Sacrifice'' by [[Daniel Maclise]]\n| titles = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place = \n| home_town = \n| residence = \n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| venerated_in = [[Judaism]]<br>[[Christianity]]<br>[[Islam]]<br>[[Mandaeism]]<br>[[Baha'i Faith]]\n| beatified_date = \n| beatified_place = \n| beatified_by = \n| canonized_date = \n| canonized_place = \n| canonized_by = \n| major_shrine = \n| feast_day = \n| attributes = \n| patronage = \n| issues = \n| suppressed_date = \n| suppressed_by = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| tradition = \n| major_works = \n}}\n\nIn [[Abrahamic religions]], '''Noah'''{{efn|{{Hebrew Name|{{Hebrew|\u05e0\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7}}|N\u014da\u1e96|N\u014da\u1e25}}; {{lang-syr|\u0722\u0718\u071a}} ''Nukh''; {{lang-am|\u1296\u1205}}, ''No\u1e25'';  {{lang-ar|\u0646\u064f\u0648\u062d}} ''{{transl|ar|ALA-LC|N\u016b\u1e25}}''; {{lang-grc|\u039d\u1ff6\u03b5}} ''N\u00f4e''}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|n|o\u028a|.|\u0259}} {{respell|NOH|\u0259}})<ref>[https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/bofm/pronunciation?lang=eng churchofjesuschrist.org: \"Book of Mormon Pronunciation Guide\"] (retrieved 2012-02-25), [[Wikipedia:IPA for English|IPA]]-ified from \u00abn\u014d\u00b4a\u00bb</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Wells|first=John C.|year=2008|title=Longman Pronunciation Dictionary|edition=3rd|publisher=Longman|isbn=9781405881180}}</ref> was the tenth and last of the [[Antediluvian|pre-Flood]] [[Patriarchs (Bible)|patriarchs]]. His story is contained in the [[Hebrew Bible]], in the [[Book of Genesis]], chapters 5\u20139 and in the [[Qur'an]]. The [[Genesis flood narrative]] is among the best-known stories of the [[Bible]]. Noah is also portrayed as \"the first tiller of the soil\" and the inventor of wine.\n\nAccording to the Genesis account, Noah labored faithfully to build the [[Noah's Ark|Ark]] at God's command, ultimately saving not only his own family, but mankind itself and all land animals, from extinction during the [[Great Flood|Flood]]. Afterwards, God made a [[Covenant (biblical)|covenant]] with him and promised never again to destroy all the earth's creatures with a flood. The flood narrative is followed by the story of the [[Curse of Ham]].\n\nIn addition to the Book of Genesis, Noah is mentioned in the Hebrew Bible in the [[Books of Chronicles|First Book of Chronicles]], and the books of [[Book of Tobit|Tobit]], [[Book of Wisdom|Wisdom]], [[Sirach]], [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]], [[Book of Ezekiel|Ezekiel]], [[2 Esdras]], [[4 Maccabees]]; in the [[New Testament]], he is mentioned in the gospels of [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]], and [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]], the [[Epistle to the Hebrews]], [[First Epistle of Peter|1st Peter]] and [[Second Epistle of Peter|2nd Peter]]. Noah was the subject of much elaboration in the literature of later Abrahamic religions, including the [[Quran]] ([[Surah]]s [[Sura 71|71]], [[Sura 7|7]], [[Sura 11|1]], and [[Sura 21|21]]).\n\n==Biblical account==\n[[File:Noah mosaic.JPG|thumb|right |12th-century Venetian [[mosaic]] depiction of Noah sending the dove]]\nThe primary account of Noah in the Bible is in the [[Book of Genesis]].\n\nNoah was the tenth of the Pre-Flood ([[Antediluvian]]) Patriarchs. His father was [[Lamech (father of Noah)|Lamech]]  and his mother is not named in the biblical accounts.<ref>Fullom, S.W. (1855). [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ELtYAAAAcAAJ&dq=History+of+Woman+religion&q=noah+mother#v=snippet&q=noah%20mother&f=false ''The History of Woman, and Her Connexion with Religion, Civilization, & Domestic Manners, from the Earliest Period'']. p.10</ref> When Noah was five hundred years old, he became the father of [[Shem]], [[Ham, son of Noah|Ham]] and [[Japheth]] ({{Bibleverse||Genesis|5:32|9}}).\n\n===Genesis flood narrative===\n{{Main|Genesis flood narrative}}\nThe Genesis flood narrative makes up chapters 6\u20139 in the [[Book of Genesis]], in the [[Bible]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Silverman|first=Jason|title=Opening Heaven's Floodgates: The Genesis Flood Narrative, Its Context, and Reception|year=2013|publisher=[[Gorgias Press]]}}</ref> The narrative, one of many [[flood myth]]s found in human cultures, indicates that [[Yahweh|God]] intended to return the [[Earth]] to its pre-Creation state of watery [[Chaos (cosmogony)|chaos]] by flooding the Earth because of humanity's misdeeds and then remake it using the microcosm of [[Noah's ark]]. Thus, the flood was no ordinary overflow but a reversal of [[Genesis creation narrative|Creation]].<ref name=\"Bandstra2008\">{{cite book|author=Barry L. Bandstra|title=Reading the Old Testament: Introduction to the Hebrew Bible|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vRY9mTUZKJcC&pg=PR19|date=2008|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-495-39105-0|page=61}}</ref> The narrative discusses the evil of mankind that moved God to destroy the world by the way of the flood, the preparation of the ark for certain animals, Noah, and his family, and God's guarantee (the [[Noahic Covenant]]) for the continued existence of life under the promise that he would never send another flood.{{sfn|Cotter|2003|pp=49, 50}}\n\n===After the flood===\n{{Main|Covenant (biblical)#Noahic covenant}}\nAfter the flood, Noah offered burnt offerings to God, who said: \"I will not again curse the ground any more for man's sake; for the imagination of man's heart ''is'' evil from his youth; neither will I again smite any more every thing living, as I have done\" ({{bibleverse-nb||Genesis|8:20\u201321|9}}).\n\n\"And God blessed Noah and his sons, and said unto them, Be fruitful, and multiply, and replenish the earth\" ({{bibleverse-nb||Genesis|9:1|9}}). They were also told that all fowls, land animals, and fishes would be afraid of them. Furthermore, as well as green plants, every moving thing would be their food with the exception that the blood was not to be eaten. Man's life blood would be required from the beasts and from man. \"Whoso sheddeth man's blood, by man shall his blood be shed: for in the image of God made he man\" (9:6). A rainbow, called \"my bow\", was given as the sign of a covenant \"between me and you and every living creature that ''[is]'' with you, for perpetual generations\" ({{bibleverse-nb||Genesis|9:2\u201317|9}}), called the Noahic covenant or the [[rainbow covenant]].\n\nNoah died 350 years after the flood, at the age of 950,<ref>{{bibleverse||Genesis|9:28\u201329|9}}</ref> the last of the extremely long-lived [[Antediluvian]] patriarchs. The maximum human lifespan, as depicted by the Bible, gradually diminishes thereafter, from almost 1,000 years to the 120 years of [[Moses]].<ref>{{bibleref2|Gen.6:3;Deut.31:22;34:37||9|Genesis 6:3; Deuteronomy 31:22; 34:37}}</ref>\n\n===Noah's drunkenness===\n[[File:Egerton Genesis Noahs Drunkeness.png|thumb|Noah's drunkenness, Ham mocks Noah, Noah is covered, Canaan is cursed. [[Egerton Genesis]]]]\nAfter the flood, the Bible says that Noah became a [[husbandman]] and he planted a vineyard. He drank wine made from this vineyard, and got drunk; and lay \"uncovered\" within his tent. Noah's son Ham, the father of Canaan, saw his father naked and told his brothers, which led to Ham's son [[Curse of Ham|Canaan being cursed]] by Noah.<ref>{{bibleverse||Genesis|9:20\u201327|9}}</ref>  As early as the [[Classical era]], commentators on {{bibleverse||Genesis|9:20\u201321|HE}} have excused Noah's excessive drinking because he was considered to be the first wine drinker; the first person to discover the effects of wine.<ref name=\"Ellen&Rollins\">Ellens & Rollins. ''Psychology and the Bible: From Freud to Kohut'', 2004, ({{ISBN|027598348X}}, 9780275983482), p.52</ref> [[John Chrysostom]], [[Archbishop of Constantinople]], and a [[Church Father]], wrote in the 4th century that Noah's behavior is defensible: as the first human to taste wine, he would not know its effects: \"Through ignorance and inexperience of the proper amount to drink, fell into a drunken stupor\".<ref>Hamilton, 1990, pp. 202\u2013203</ref>\n\n[[Philo]], a [[Hellenistic philosophy|Hellenistic]] Jewish philosopher, also excused Noah by noting that one can drink in two different manners: (1) to drink wine in excess, a peculiar sin to the vicious evil man or (2) to partake of wine as the wise man, Noah being the latter.<ref>''Philo'', 1971, p. 160</ref>\n\nIn [[Jewish tradition]] and [[Noah in rabbinic literature#His lapse|rabbinic literature on Noah]], rabbis blame [[Satan]] for the intoxicating properties of the wine.<ref>Gen. Rabbah 36:3</ref><ref name=\"Noah's wine JewEnyc\">{{Cite web|url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/11571-noah|title=NOAH - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n\n===Curse of Ham===\n{{main|Curse of Ham}}\n[[File:Noah-Curses-Ham.jpg|thumb|left|''Noah curses Ham'' by [[Gustave Dore]]]]\nIn the field of [[psychological biblical criticism]], [[J. Harold Ellens|J. H. Ellens]] and W. G. Rollins address the narrative of {{Bibleverse||Genesis|9:18\u201327|HE}} that narrates the unconventional behavior that occurs between Noah and Ham. Because of its brevity and textual inconsistencies, it has been suggested that this narrative is a \"splinter from a more substantial tale\".<ref>Speiser, 1964, 62</ref><ref>T. A. Bergren. ''Biblical Figures Outside the Bible'', 2002, ({{ISBN|1563384116}}, {{ISBN|978-1-56338-411-0}}), p. 136</ref> A fuller account would explain what exactly Ham had done to his father, or why Noah directed a curse at [[Canaan (son of Ham)|Canaan]] for Ham's misdeed, or how Noah came to know what occurred. The narrator relates two facts: (1) Noah became drunken and \"he was uncovered within his tent\", and (2) Ham \"saw the nakedness of his father, and told his two brethren without\". Thus, these passages revolve around sexuality and the exposure of genitalia as compared with other Hebrew Bible texts, such as {{Bibleverse|Habakkuk|2:15|HE}} and {{Bibleverse|Lamentations|4:21|HE}}.<ref>Ellens & Rollins, 2004, p.53</ref>\n\nOther commentaries mention that seeing someone's nakedness could mean having sex with that person as quoted in {{Bibleverse|Leviticus|18:7-8|HE}} and {{Bibleverse|Leviticus|20:11|HE}}. From this interpretation, it can be deduced that Ham was guilty of engaging in incest and raping Noah.<ref>Levenson, 2004, 26</ref>\n\n===Table of nations===\n[[File:Noahsworld map.jpg|thumb|right|The dispersion of the descendants of Shem, Ham, and Japheth (map from the 1854 ''Historical Textbook and Atlas of Biblical Geography'')]]\n{{See also|Generations of Noah}}\n{{Bibleverse||Genesis|10|HE}} sets forth the descendants of Shem, Ham, and Japheth, from whom the nations branched out over the earth after the flood. Among Japheth\u2019s descendants were the maritime nations. (10:2\u20135) Ham\u2019s son [[Biblical Cush|Cush]] had a son named [[Nimrod]], who became the first man of might on earth, a mighty hunter, king in [[Babylon]] and the land of [[Shinar]]. (10:6\u201310) From there [[Ashur|Asshur]] went and built [[Nineveh]]. (10:11\u201312) Canaan\u2019s descendants{{snd}} Sidon, [[Biblical Hittites|Heth]], the [[Jebusite]]s, the [[Amorite]]s, the Girgashites, the [[Hivites]], the Arkites, the Sinites, the Arvadites, the Zemarites, and the Hamathites{{snd}} spread out from [[Sidon]] as far as [[Gerar]], near [[Gaza City|Gaza]], and as far as [[Sodom and Gomorrah]]. (10:15\u201319) Among Shem\u2019s descendants was [[Eber]]. (10:21)\n\nThese genealogies differ structurally from those set out in Genesis 5 and 11. It has a segmented or treelike structure, going from one father to many offspring. It is strange that the table, which assumes that the population is distributed about the Earth, precedes the account of the [[Tower of Babel]], which says that all the population is in one place before it is dispersed.<ref>{{citation |last=Bandstra |first=B. |url=https://books.google.com/?id=vRY9mTUZKJcC&pg=PA67#v=onepage&q=%22table%20of%20nations%22%20noah&f=false |title=Reading the Old Testament: Introduction to the Hebrew Bible |publisher= Cengage Learning |year=2008 |pages= 67\u201368|isbn=978-0495391050 }}</ref>\n\n==Family tree==\n{{AdamtoNoah}}\n\n==Narrative analysis==\nAccording to the [[documentary hypothesis]], the first five books of the Bible ([[Pentateuch]]/[[Torah]]), including Genesis, were collated during the 5th century BC from four main sources, which themselves date from no earlier than the 10th century BC. Two of these, the [[Jahwist]], composed in the 10th century BC, and the [[Priestly source]], from the late 7th century BC, make up the chapters of Genesis which concern Noah. The attempt by the 5th-century editor to accommodate two independent and sometimes conflicting sources accounts for the confusion over such matters as how many of each animal Noah took, and how long the flood lasted.<ref>{{cite book |title= Introduction to the Hebrew Bible|last= Collins|first= John J.|year= 2004|publisher= Fortress Press|location= Minneapolis|isbn= 0-8006-2991-4|pages= 56\u201357}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title= Who Wrote the Bible?|last= Friedman|first= Richard Elliotty|year= 1989|publisher= HarperCollins Publishers|location= New York|isbn= 0-06-063035-3|page= [https://archive.org/details/whowrotebible000frie/page/59 59]|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/whowrotebible000frie/page/59}}</ref>\n\n''The Oxford Encyclopedia of the Books of the Bible'' notes that this story echoes parts of the [[Garden of Eden]] story: Noah is the first vintner, while Adam is the first farmer; both have problems with their produce; both stories involve nakedness; and both involve a division between brothers leading to a curse. However, after the flood, the stories differ. Noah plants the vineyard and utters the curse, not God, so \"God is less involved\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/?id=SNFMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=noah%20&f=false ''The Oxford Encyclopedia of the Books of the Bible''], Oxford University Press, 2011, p. 318.</ref>\n\n==Other accounts==\nNoah appears in several non-canonical books.\n\n===Pseudepigrapha===\nThe [[Book of Jubilees]] refers to Noah and says that he was taught the arts of healing by an angel so that his children could overcome \"the offspring of the [[Watcher (angel)|Watchers]]\".<ref>Lewis, Jack Pearl, [https://books.google.com/?id=mO_H2lVTyhkC&pg=PA14#v=snippet&q=%22seems%20to%20have%20little%22&f=false ''A Study of the Interpretation of Noah and the Flood in Jewish and Christian Literature''], BRILL, 1968, p. 14.</ref>\n\nIn 10:1\u20133 of the [[Book of Enoch]] (which is part of the [[Orthodox Tewahedo biblical canon]]), [[Uriel]] was dispatched by \"the Most High\" to inform Noah of the approaching \"deluge\".<ref>{{cite book |chapter=[[s:Book of Enoch/Chapter 10|Chapter X]] |title=The Book of Enoch |others= translated by [[Robert Charles (scholar)|Robert H. Charles]] |location=London |publisher=Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge|year=1917 }}</ref>\n\n===Dead Sea scrolls===\n[[File:Genesis apocryphon.jpg|thumb|[[Genesis Apocryphon]], a portion of the [[Dead Sea Scrolls]] that features Noah]]\nThere are 20 or so fragments of the [[Dead Sea scrolls]] that appear to refer to Noah.<ref>Peters, DM., [https://books.google.com/?id=MXU3PTrFe6gC#v=snippet&q=%22words%20on%20noah%22%20twenty&f=false ''Noah Traditions in the Dead Sea Scrolls: Conversations and Controversies of Antiquity''], Society of Biblical Lit, 2008, pp. 15\u201317.</ref> [[Lawrence Schiffman]] writes, \"Among the Dead Sea Scrolls at least three different versions of this legend are preserved.\"<ref>Schiffman, LH., [https://books.google.com/?id=jAsaAwAAQBAJ#v=snippet&q=613%20second&f=false ] ''Encyclopedia of the Dead Sea Scrolls, Volume 2'], Granite Hill Publishers, 2000, pp. 613\u2013614.</ref> In particular, \"The [[Genesis Apocryphon]] devotes considerable space to Noah.\" However, \"The material seems to have little in common with Genesis 5 which reports the birth of Noah.\" Also, Noah's father is reported as worrying that his son was actually fathered by one of the [[Watcher (angel)|Watchers]].<ref>Lewis, Jack Pearl, [https://books.google.com/books?id=mO_H2lVTyhkC&pg=PA11#v=snippet&q=%22the%20offspring%20of%20the%20Watchers%22&f=false ''A Study of the Interpretation of Noah and the Flood in Jewish and Christian Literature''], BRILL, 1968, p. 11. \"the offspring of the Watchers\"</ref>\n\n==Comparative mythology==\n{{Main|Flood myth}}\nIndian and Greek flood-myths also exist, although there is little evidence that they were derived from the Mesopotamian flood-myth that underlies the biblical account.<ref>Frazer, JG., in Dundes, A (ed.),\n[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=E__dnnQwGDwC&dq=frazer+noah&q=%22there+is+little+evidence%22#v=snippet&q=%22there%20is%20little%20evidence%22&f=false ''The Flood Myth''], University of California Press, 1988,\npp. 121\u2013122.</ref>\n\n===Mesopotamian===\n[[File:Mr. George Smith, the man who transliterated and read the so-called the Babylonian Flood Story of Tablet XI.jpg|thumb|[[George Smith (Assyriologist)|George Smith]], who transliterated and read the so-called \"Babylonian Flood Story\" of Tablet XI of the [[Epic of Gilgamesh]]]]\nThe Noah story of the Pentateuch is almost identical to a flood story contained in the Mesopotamian [[Epic of Gilgamesh]], composed about 2000 BC. In the Gilgamesh version, the [[Mesopotamian gods]] are enraged by the noise that man has raised from the earth. To quiet them they decide to send a great flood to silence mankind. Various correlations between the stories of Noah and Gilgamesh (the flood, the construction of the ark, the salvation of animals, and the release of birds following the flood) have led to this story being seen as the inspiration for the story of Noah. The few variations include the number of days of the deluge, the order of the birds, and the name of the mountain on which the ark rests. The flood story in Genesis 6\u20138 matches the [[Gilgamesh flood myth]] so closely that \"few doubt that [it] derives from a Mesopotamian account.\"<ref name=\"George2003\">{{cite book|first==A. R. |last=George|title=The Babylonian Gilgamesh Epic: Introduction, Critical Edition and Cuneiform Texts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=21xxZ_gUy_wC&pg=PA70|accessdate=8 November 2012|year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-927841-1|page=70 |via=Google Books}}</ref> What is particularly noticeable is the way the Genesis flood story follows the Gilgamesh flood tale \"point by point and in the same order\", even when the story permits other alternatives.<ref>Rendsburg, Gary. \"The Biblical flood story in the light of the Gilgamesh flood account,\" in ''Gilgamesh and the world of Assyria'', eds Azize, J & Weeks, N. Peters, 2007, p. 117</ref>\n\nThe earliest written [[flood myth]] is found in the [[Mesopotamian]] [[Epic of Atrahasis]] and [[Epic of Gilgamesh]] texts. The ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' says \"These mythologies are the source of such features of the biblical Flood story as the building and provisioning of the ark, its flotation, and the subsidence of the waters, as well as the part played by the human protagonist.\"<ref>''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'': [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/416799/Noah Noah].</ref> The ''Encyclopedia Judaica'' adds that there is a strong suggestion that \"an intermediate agent was active. The people most likely to have fulfilled this role are the [[Hurrian]]s, whose territory included the city of [[Haran]], where the Patriarch [[Abraham]] had his roots. The Hurrians inherited the Flood story from Babylonia\".<ref name=Skolnik287 />\nThe encyclopedia mentions another similarity between the stories: Noah is the tenth patriarch and [[Berossus]] notes that \"the hero of the great flood was Babylonia\u2019s tenth antediluvian king.\" However, there is a discrepancy in the ages of the heroes. For the Mesopotamian antecedents, \"the reigns of the antediluvian kings range from 18,600 to nearly 65,000 years.\" In the Bible, the lifespans \"fall far short of the briefest reign mentioned in the related Mesopotamian texts.\" Also, the name of the hero differs between the traditions: \"The earliest Mesopotamian flood account, written in the Sumerian language, calls the deluge hero [[Ziusudra]].\"<ref name=Skolnik287 />\n\n[[Gilgamesh]]\u2019s historical reign is believed to have been approximately 2700 BC,<ref>Georges Roux, ''Ancient Iraq'', pages 123, 502</ref> shortly before the earliest known written stories. The discovery of artifacts associated with [[Aga of Kish|Aga]] and [[Enmebaragesi]] of [[Kish (Sumer)|Kish]], two other kings named in the stories, has lent credibility to the historical existence of Gilgamesh.<ref>[[Stephanie Dalley|Dalley, Stephanie]], ''Myths from Mesopotamia'', Oxford University Press (1989), p. 40\u201341</ref>\n\nThe earliest [[Sumer]]ian Gilgamesh poems date from as early as the [[Third dynasty of Ur]] (2100\u20132000 BC).<ref>Andrew George, page xix</ref> One of these poems mentions Gilgamesh\u2019s journey to meet the flood hero, as well as a short version of the flood story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/etcsl.cgi?text=t.1.8.1.3#|title=The Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|website=etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk}}</ref> The earliest [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] versions of the unified epic are dated to ca. 2000\u20131500 BC.<ref>Andrew George, page 101, \"Early Second Millennium BC\" in Old Babylonian</ref> Due to the fragmentary nature of these Old Babylonian versions, it is unclear whether they included an expanded account of the flood myth; although one fragment definitely includes the story of Gilgamesh\u2019s journey to meet [[Utnapishtim]]. The \"standard\" Akkadian version included a long version of the flood story and was edited by [[Sin-liqe-unninni]] sometime between 1300 and 1000 BC.<ref>Andrew George, pages xxiv\u2013xxv</ref>\n\n===Ancient Greek===\nNoah has often been compared to [[Deucalion]], the son of [[Prometheus]] and [[Pronoia]] in [[Greek mythology]]. Like Noah, Deucalion is warned of the flood (by [[Zeus]] and [[Poseidon]]); he builds an ark and staffs it with creatures \u2013 and when he completes his voyage, gives thanks and takes advice from the gods on how to repopulate the Earth. Deucalion also sends a pigeon to find out about the situation of the world and the bird returns with an olive branch.<ref>''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/159650/Deucalion Deucalion].</ref><ref>Wajdenbaum, P., [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=3kiPBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA92&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3#v=onepage&q=noah&f=false ''Argonauts of the Desert: Structural Analysis of the Hebrew Bible''], Routledge, 2014, pp. 104\u2013108.</ref> Deucalion, in some versions of the myth, also becomes the inventor of wine, like Noah.<ref>Anderson, G., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G9IQt92pbjwC&pg=PA130&dq=noah+deucalion&hl=en&sa=X&ei=BkykVOSEEor0UPvkgbgK&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAjgU#v=onepage&q=noah%20deucalion&f=false ''Greek and Roman Folklore: A Handbook''], Greenwood Publishing Group, 2006. pp. 129\u2013130.</ref> [[Philo]]<ref>Lewis, JP.; Lewis, JP., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mO_H2lVTyhkC&pg=PA101&dq=the+Interpretation+of+Noah&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zLOqVK-iH4byUKXXgrAL&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=philo%20noah&f=false ''A Study of the Interpretation of Noah and the Flood in Jewish and Christian Literature''], BRILL, 1968, p. 47.</ref> and [[Justin (historian)|Justin]] equate Deucalion with Noah, and [[Josephus]] used the story of Deucalion as evidence that the flood actually occurred and that, therefore, Noah existed.<ref>Peters, DM., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MXU3PTrFe6gC&pg=PA4&dq=deucalion+noah&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5-SmVMeWBcb0UqaAgrAO&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=manu%20noah&f=false ''Noah Traditions in the Dead Sea Scrolls: Conversations and Controversies of Antiquity''], Society of Biblical Lit, 2008, p. 4.</ref><ref>Feldman, LH., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=S349d-yRgCIC&pg=PA166&dq=noah+josephus&hl=en&sa=X&ei=vcCqVIXgLcKAU_7Lg6AL&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=deucalion&f=false ''Josephus's Interpretation of the Bible''], University of California Press, 1998, p. 133.</ref>\n\n===Hindu===\nA story involving Lord [[Vishnu]] and King [[Sraddhadeva Manu|Manu]] is found in the [[Hindu]] chronicle [[Matsya Purana]]. Lord Vishnu in his 'matsya' (fish) [[avatar]] ordered the virtuous king Manu to construct a huge boat with animal and plant specimens of all forms, to escape the Great Deluge, and finally when the water receded, the great boat was found atop the [[Malaya Mountains]].<ref>Frazer. RW., [https://books.google.com/?id=9bkiKm3cA_EC&pg=PA83#v=onepage&q=manu%20noah&f=false ''A Literary History of India''], Mittal Publications, 1898, pp. 83\u201384.</ref> ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' notes that \"Manu combines the characteristics of the Hebrew Bible figures of Noah, who preserved life from extinction in a great flood, and Adam, the first man\",<ref>''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/363047/Manu Manu]</ref> which view is reflected in several other works.<ref>Ananda, SG., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qelsBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA180&dq=noah+manu&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fQOkVPfLEYH9UrKUgLAN&ved=0CDsQ6AEwBTgK#v=snippet&q=noah%20manu&f=false ''Brahma: The God of Abraham''], Art of Unity, 2014, pp. 177 \u2013 180.</ref> [[Indologist]] [[David Shulman|David Dean Shulman]] writes that borrowing between the myths of Manu and Noah \"cannot be ruled out\".<ref>Shulman, DD, in Dundes, A. (ed), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=E__dnnQwGDwC&pg=PA296&dq=manu+flood&hl=en&sa=X&ei=dhKlVIKtHYHqULLggfAK&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=manu%20flood&f=false ''The Flood Myth''], University of California Press, 1988, p. 296.</ref>\nFor [[Krishna Mohan Banerjee]], the names \"Noah\" and \"Manu\" \"had the same etymological root: 'Manu' must have been the Indo-Aryan ideal of Noah.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Sugirtharajah|first=R. S.|authorlink=R. S. Sugirtharajah|title=The Bible and the Third World: Precolonial, Colonial and Postcolonial Encounters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d0pJETntV8sC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-00524-1|page=93}}</ref> Philologist and founder of the [[Asiatic Society of Bengal]], [[William Jones (philologist)|William Jones]], \"identifies Manu with Noah\", along with whom, \"the seven sages can be identified with the eight people aboard the Ark.\"<ref>Trautmann. TR., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dhbwDFfE9J8C&pg=PA58&dq=noah+manu&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3fyjVOvAF8urU4f_grAL&ved=0CFIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=noah%20manu&f=false ''Aryans and British India''], Yoda Press, 2006 p. 58.</ref> Furthermore, researcher [[Klaus Klostermaier]] reports a Muslim writer who \"identifies Brahma with Abraham .... and Manu with Noah.\"<ref>Klostermaier, K., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8CVviRghVtIC&dq=manu+flood&q=noah+manu#v=snippet&q=noah%20manu&f=false ''A Survey of Hinduism: Third Edition''], SUNY Press, 2010, p. 406.</ref> Others, however, would say that \"the story is thoroughly Indian\" and the \"boat is not the equivalent of Noah's Ark, though it is still the symbol of salvation\"<ref>Bonnefoy, Y., [https://books.google.com/?id=r4I-FsZCzJEC&pg=PA80#v=onepage&q=noah&f=false ''Asian Mythologies''], University of Chicago Press, 1993, p. 80.</ref> According to Purana Manu's story occur before 28 chaturyuga in the present Manvantara which is the 7th Manvantara. This amounts to 120 million years ago.<ref>{{cite web|title=G. P. Bhatt (ed.), The vayu purana, part-II, 1st ed., 784\u2014789, tr. G. V. Tagare. In vol.38 of Ancient Indian Tradition and Mythology, Delhi: Motilal Banarsidass, 1988.|url=https://www.mlbd.com/BookDecription.aspx?id=1728|accessdate=10 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121150747/https://www.mlbd.com/BookDecription.aspx?id=1728|archive-date=21 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=J. L. Shastri (ed.), The kurma-purana, part-I, 1st ed., 47\u201452, tr. G. V. Tagare. In vol.20 of A.I.T.&M., Delhi: Motilal Banarsidass, 1981.|url=https://www.mlbd.com/BookDecription.aspx?id=1728|accessdate=10 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121150747/https://www.mlbd.com/BookDecription.aspx?id=1728|archive-date=21 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=J. L. Shastri (ed.), The Narada purana, part-II, 1st ed., p. 699, tr. G. V. Tagare. In vol.16 of A.I.T.&M., Delhi: Motilal Banarsidass, 1981.|url=https://www.mlbd.com/BookDecription.aspx?id=1728|accessdate=10 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121150747/https://www.mlbd.com/BookDecription.aspx?id=1728|archive-date=21 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Religious views==\n\n===Judaism===\n{{See also|Noah in rabbinic literature|Noach (parsha)}}\n[[File:Ararat Ms. 11639 521a.jpg|205px|left|thumb|A Jewish depiction of Noah]]\nThe righteousness of Noah is the subject of much discussion among rabbis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/11571-noah#anchor5|title=NOAH - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref> The description of Noah as \"righteous in his generation\" implied to some that his perfection was only relative: In his generation of wicked people, he could be considered righteous, but in the generation of a ''[[tzadik]]'' like [[Abraham]], he would not be considered so righteous. They point out that Noah did not pray to God on behalf of those about to be destroyed, as Abraham prayed for the wicked of [[Sodom and Gomorrah]]. In fact, Noah is never seen to speak; he simply listens to God and acts on his orders. This led some commentators to offer the figure of Noah as \"the man in a fur coat,\" who ensured his own comfort while ignoring his neighbour.<ref>Mamet, D., Kushner, L., [https://books.google.com/?id=Gr0SAQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=+%22man+in+a+fur+coat%22 ''Five Cities of Refuge: Weekly Reflections on Genesis, Exodus, Leviticus, Numbers, and Deuteronomy''], Schocken Books, 2003, p. 1.</ref> Others, such as the medieval commentator [[Rashi]], held on the contrary that the building of the Ark was stretched over 120 years, deliberately in order to give sinners time to repent. Rashi interprets his father's statement of the naming of Noah (in Hebrew \u05e0\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7) \"This one will comfort us (in Hebrew\u2013 yeNaHamainu \u05d9\u05b0\u05e0\u05b7\u05d7\u05b2\u05de\u05b5\u05e0\u05d5) in our work and in the toil of our hands, which come from the ground that the Lord had cursed\",<ref>{{bibleverse||Genesis|5:29|9}}</ref> by saying Noah heralded a new era of prosperity, when there was easing (in Hebrew \u2013 nahah \u2013 \u05e0\u05d7\u05d4) from the curse from the time of Adam when the Earth produced thorns and thistles even where men sowed wheat and that Noah then introduced the plow.<ref>Frishman, J., Rompay, L. von, [https://books.google.com/?id=SqThaPjXFyQC&pg=PA63#v=onepage&q=noah%20righteous&f=false ''The Book of Genesis in Jewish and Oriental Christian Interpretation: A Collection of Essays''], Peeters Publishers, 1997, pp. 62\u201365.</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]'', \"The [[Book of Genesis]] contains two accounts of Noah.\" In the first, Noah is the hero of the flood, and in the second, he is the father of mankind and a husbandman who planted the first vineyard. \"The disparity of character between these two narratives has caused some critics to insist that the subject of the latter account was not the same as the subject of the former.\" Perhaps the original name of the hero of the flood was actually ''Enoch''.<ref>''Jewish Encyclopedia'': Noah. [http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/11571-noah#anchor11 Critical View]</ref>\n\nThe [[Encyclopedia Judaica]] notes that Noah's drunkenness is not presented as reprehensible behavior. Rather, \"It is clear that ... Noah\u2019s venture into viticulture provides the setting for the castigation of Israel\u2019s Canaanite neighbors.\" It was Ham who committed an offense when he viewed his father\u2019s nakedness. Yet, \"Noah\u2019s curse, ... is strangely aimed at Canaan rather than the disrespectful Ham.\"<ref name=Skolnik287 />\n\n===Christianity===\n[[File:Noah catacombe.jpg|150px|right|thumb|An early Christian depiction showing Noah giving the gesture of [[orant]] as the dove returns]]\n[http://www.bibler.org/versions/nasb/nasb_2peter02_sml.htm#2peter_2:5 2 Peter 2:5] refers to Noah as a \"preacher of righteousness\". In the Gospel of Matthew and the Gospel of Luke, Jesus compares Noah's flood with the coming [[Last Judgement|Day of Judgement]]: \"Just as it was in the days of Noah, so too it will be in the days of the coming of the [[Son of man (Christianity)|Son of Man]]. For in the days before the flood, people were eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage, up to the day Noah entered the ark; and they knew nothing about what would happen until the flood came and took them all away. That is how it will be at the coming of the Son of Man.\"<ref>Matthew 24:38</ref><ref>Luke 17:26</ref>\n\nThe [[First Epistle of Peter]] compares the power of [[baptism]] with the Ark saving those who were in it. In later Christian thought, the Ark came to be compared to the [[Christian Church|Church]]: [[Salvation in Christianity|salvation]] was to be found only within Christ and his Lordship, as in Noah's time it had been found only within the Ark. [[St Augustine of Hippo]] (354\u2013430), demonstrated in ''[[The City of God (book)|The City of God]]'' that the dimensions of the Ark corresponded to the dimensions of the human body, which corresponds to the [[body of Christ]]; the equation of Ark and Church is still found in the [[Anglican]] rite of baptism, which asks God, \"who of thy great mercy didst save Noah,\" to receive into the Church the infant about to be baptised.<ref>Peters, DM., [https://books.google.com/?id=MXU3PTrFe6gC#v=snippet&q=nuanced%20%22temple%20period%22%20%22and%20early%20christianity%22&f=false ''Noah Traditions in the Dead Sea Scrolls: Conversations and Controversies of Antiquity''], Society of Biblical Lit, 2008, pp. 15\u201317.</ref>\n\nIn [[History of medieval Christianity|medieval Christianity]], Noah's three sons were generally considered as the founders of the populations of the three known [[continent]]s, [[Japheth]]/Europe, [[Shem]]/Asia, and [[Ham (son of Noah)|Ham]]/Africa, although a rarer variation held that they represented the three classes of medieval society \u2013 the priests (Shem), the warriors (Japheth), and the peasants (Ham). In medieval Christian thought, Ham was considered to be the ancestor of the people of black Africa. So, in racialist arguments, the curse of Ham became a justification for the slavery of the black races.<ref>Jackson, JP., Weidman, NM., [https://books.google.com/?id=g4WalMw26IkC&pg=PA4#v=onepage&q=noah%20christianity%20medieval%20shem&f=false ''Race, Racism, and Science: Social Impact and Interaction''], ABC-CLIO, 2004, p. 4.</ref>\n\n[[Isaac Newton]], in his religious works on the development of religion, wrote about Noah and his offspring. In Newton's view, while Noah was a monotheist, the gods of pagan antiquity are identified with Noah and his descendants.<ref>{{citation |last=Force |first=J E |chapter=Essay 12: Newton, the \"Ancients\" and the \"Moderns\"  |editor-last1= Popkin |editor-first1=RH |editor-last2=Force |editor-first2=JE |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=gJKaqMDxyL0C&pg=PA254#v=onepage&q=noah%20religion&f=false |title=Newton and Religion: Context, Nature, and Influence |publisher=Kluwer |year=1999 |pages=253\u2013254 |via=Google Books |series=International Archive of the History of Ideas |number =161}}</ref>\n\n====Mormon theology====\nIn [[Mormonism|Mormon theology]], Noah plays an important role, prior to his birth, as the angel [[Gabriel]], and then lived in his mortal life as the patriarch-prophet Noah. Gabriel and Noah are regarded as the same individual under different names.<ref>{{citation |contribution-url= https://www.lds.org/scriptures/bd/noah?lang=eng |contribution= Noah |title= Bible Dictionary |series= [[LDS edition of the Bible|KJV (LDS)]] |publisher= [[LDS Church]] |title-link= Bible Dictionary (LDS Church) }}</ref><ref>{{citation |contribution-url= https://www.lds.org/scriptures/gs/noah-bible-patriarch?lang=eng |contribution= Noah, Bible Patriarch |title= Study Helps: The Guide to the Scriptures |series= [[Standard works]] |publisher= [[LDS Church]] }}</ref> [[Mormons]] also believe that Noah returned to earth as Gabriel after his earthly life<ref>{{citation |chapter-url= https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/manual/teachings-joseph-smith/chapter-8?lang=eng |chapter= Chapter 8: The Everlasting Priesthood |title= Teachings of Presidents of the Church: Joseph Smith |year= 2001 |pages= 101\u2013113 |publisher= LDS Church |title-link= Teachings of Presidents of the Church: Joseph Smith }}</ref> and appeared to [[Daniel (biblical figure)|Daniel]] to teach him about the [[Second Coming]]; to [[Zechariah (priest)|Zacharias]], the father of [[John the Baptist]]; and to [[Latter Day Saint views on Mary|Mary]], the mother of Jesus.<ref>{{citation |url= https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/2014/02/noah?lang=eng |title= Old Testament Prophets: Noah |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |date= February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nNoah is considered the head of a [[Dispensation (period)|dispensation]] along with [[Adam and Eve (LDS Church)|Adam]], [[Enoch (ancestor of Noah)|Enoch]], [[Abraham]], [[Moses]], [[Jesus]] and [[Joseph Smith]]. A dispensation is a period of time in which the Lord has at least one authorized servant on earth who bears the keys of the holy priesthood.<ref>{{citation |contribution-url= https://www.lds.org/scriptures/gs/dispensation?lang=eng |contribution= Dispensation |title= Study Helps: The Guide to the Scriptures |series= [[Standard works]] |publisher= LDS Church }}</ref> Noah became the means by which the gospel of Jesus Christ\u2014 the [[plan of salvation (Latter Day Saints)|plan of salvation]] \u2014is revealed anew, the means by which divine transforming powers, including saving covenants and ordinances, are extended to people during an age of time called a dispensation.<ref>{{citation |url= https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1994/06/joseph-smith-among-the-prophets?lang=eng |title= Joseph Smith among the Prophets |first= Robert L. |last= Millet |authorlink= Robert L. Millet |journal= [[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] |date= June 1994 }}</ref>\n\n===Islam===\n{{Main|Noah in Islam}}\n[[File:Noah's Ark by Miskin.jpg|thumb|left|An Islamic depiction of Noah in a 16th-century [[Mughal painting|Mughal miniature]].]]\nNoah is a highly important figure in [[Islam]] and he is seen as one of the most significant of all prophets. The [[Quran]] contains 43 references to Noah, or ''Nu\u1e25'', in 28 chapters, and the seventy-first chapter, [[Nuh (surah)|''S\u016brah N\u016b\u1e25'']] ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0646\u0648\u062d}}), is named after him. His life is also spoken of in the commentaries and in Islamic legends.\n\nNoah's narratives largely cover his preaching as well the story of the [[Flood myth|Deluge]]. Noah's narrative sets the prototype for many of the subsequent prophetic stories, which begin with the prophet warning his people and then the community rejecting the message and facing a punishment.\n\nNoah has several titles in Islam, based primarily on praise for him in the Quran, including \"True Messenger of God\" (XXVI: 107) and \"Grateful Servant of God\" (XVII: 3).<ref name=Skolnik287 >{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Skolnik|first1=Fred|last2=Berenbaum|first2=Michael|title=Encyclopaedia Judaica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JD0OAQAAMAAJ|year=2007|publisher=Macmillan Reference USA|isbn=978-0-02-865943-5|pages=287\u2013291}}</ref><ref name=\"Enc Islam\">{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Gibb|first=Hamilton Alexander Rosskeen|authorlink=Hamilton Alexander Rosskeen Gibb|title=The Encyclopaedia of Islam: NED-SAM|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OO4pAQAAMAAJ|year=1995|publisher=Brill|pages=108\u2013109}}</ref>\n\nThe Quran focuses on several instances from Noah's life more than others, and one of the most significant events is the Flood. God makes a [[covenant (biblical)|covenant]] with Noah just as he did with Abraham, [[Moses in Islam|Moses]], [[Jesus in Islam|Jesus]] and [[Muhammad in Islam|Muhammad]] later on (33:7). Noah is later reviled by his people and reproached by them for being a mere human messenger and not an angel (10:72\u201374). Moreover, the people mock Noah's words and call him a liar (7:62), and they even suggest that Noah is possessed by a devil when the prophet ceases to preach (54:9). Only the lowest in the community join Noah in believing in God's message (11:29), and Noah's narrative further describes him preaching both in private and public. Noah prays to God, \"Lord, leave not one single family of Infidels from the land: / For if thou leave them they will beguile thy servants and will beget only sinners, infidels.\"{{dead link|date=March 2017}}<ref>[https://http//www.quranbrowser.com/%20%22family 71:26\u201327 Rodwell 1876 version]{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The Quran narrates that Noah received a revelation to build an [[Noah's Ark|Ark]], after his people refused to believe in his message and hear the warning. The narrative goes on to describe that waters poured forth from the Heavens, destroying all the sinners. Even one of his sons disbelieved him, stayed behind, and was drowned. After the Flood ended, the Ark rested atop [[Mount Judi]] ({{cite quran|11|44|s=ns}}).\n[[File:Noah's ark and the deluge.JPG|thumb|Noah's ark and the deluge from Zubdat-al Tawarikh]]\nAlso, Islamic beliefs deny the idea of Noah being the first person to drink wine and experience the aftereffects of doing so.<ref name=Skolnik287 /><ref name = \"Enc Islam\"/>\n\n{{cite quran|29|14|s=ns}} states that Noah had been living among the people who he was sent to for 950 years when the flood started.\n{{quote|And, indeed, [in times long past] We sent forth Noah unto his people, and he dwelt among them a thousand years bar fifty; and then the floods overwhelmed them while they were still lost in evildoing.}}\n\nAccording to the [[Ahmadiyya]] understanding of the Quran, the period described in the Quran is the age of his [[Dispensation (period)|dispensation]], which extended until the time of [[Abraham in Islam|Ibrahim]] (Abraham, 950 years). The first 50 years were the years of spiritual progress, which were followed by 900 years of spiritual deterioration of the people of Noah.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://www.alislam.org/library/books/HadhratNuh.pdf | title=Hadhrat Nuh | author=Rashid Ahmad Chaudhry | publisher=Islam International Publications |isbn=1-85372-758-X}}</ref>\n\n===Gnostic===\nAn important Gnostic text, the ''[[Apocryphon of John]]'', reports that the chief [[archon (Gnosticism)|archon]] caused the flood because he desired to destroy the world he had made, but the First Thought informed Noah of the chief archon's plans, and Noah informed the remainder of humanity. Unlike the account of Genesis, not only are Noah's family saved, but many others also heed Noah's call. There is no ark in this account. According to [[Elaine Pagels]], \"Rather, they hid in a particular place, not only Noah, but also many other people from the unshakable race. They entered that place and hid in a bright cloud.\"<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Pagels|first=Elaine|authorlink=Elaine Pagels|title=The Gnostic Gospels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sOfrvFT7RVYC|year=2013|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-1-78022-670-5|page=163}}</ref>\n\n===Bah\u00e1'\u00ed===\nThe [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]] regards the Ark and the Flood as symbolic.<ref>From a letter written on behalf of Shoghi Effendi, October 28, 1949: Bah\u00e1'\u00ed News, No. 228, February 1950, p. 4. Republished in {{harvnb|Compilation |1983|p=508}}</ref> In Bah\u00e1'\u00ed belief, only Noah's followers were spiritually alive, preserved in the ark of his teachings, as others were spiritually dead.<ref>{{cite web|first = Brent|last = Poirier|title = The Kitab-i-Iqan: The key to unsealing the mysteries of the Holy Bible|url = http://bahai-library.com/poirier_iqan_unsealing_bible|accessdate = 2007-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Shoghi Effendi |authorlink=Shoghi Effendi |year=1971 |title=Messages to the Bah\u00e1'\u00ed World, 1950\u20131957 |publisher=Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Publishing Trust |location=Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn=0-87743-036-5 |url=http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/se/MBW/ |page=104}}</ref> The Bah\u00e1'\u00ed scripture ''[[Kit\u00e1b-i-\u00cdq\u00e1n]]'' endorses the Islamic belief that Noah had a large number of companions, either 40 or 72, besides his family on the Ark, and that he taught for 950 (symbolic) years before the flood.<ref>From a letter written on behalf of Shoghi Effendi to an individual believer, November 25, 1950. Published in {{harvnb|Compilation |1983|p=494}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Religion|Christianity|Islam|Judaism|Latter Day Saints}}\n* [[Atra-Hasis]], the central character in one version of the Akkadian flood myth\n* [[Bergelmir]], a [[Norse mythology|mythological Norse]] version of Noah.\n* [[Mannus]], an ancestral figure in [[Germanic mythology]]\n* [[Manu (Hinduism)|Manu]], the central character in the Hindu flood myth\n* [[Noah's wine]], a term that refers to an [[alcoholic beverage]].\n* [[Nu'u]], a [[Hawaiian religion|mythological Hawaiian]] character who built an ark and escaped a Great Flood.\n* [[Patriarchal age]]\n* [[Searches for Noah's Ark]], sometimes referred to as arkeology\n* [[Seven Laws of Noah]]\n* [[Tomb of Noah]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n{{Refbegin |2}}\n*{{cite book |last=Alter |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Alter |title=The Five Books of Moses |year=2008 |publisher=W. W. Norton & Company |isbn=978-0-393-33393-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZcMhkJ8a708C&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q=justify%20Canaan&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Brett |first=Mark G. |title=Genesis: Procreation and the Politics of Identity |year=2000 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0203992029 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nFDW1lqNEXYC&pg=PA45#v=snippet&q=Canaan&f=false |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |author=Compilation |editor-last=Hornby |editor-first=Helen |year=1983 |title=Lights of Guidance: A Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Reference File |publisher=Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Publishing Trust, New Delhi, India |isbn=81-85091-46-3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=MZ7g-BIfXu0C#v=onepage&q=Noah%27s%20Flood%3A%20The%20Genesis%20Story%20in%20Western%20Thought&f=false}}* {{Cite book |last=Dimant |first=Devorah |chapter=Noah in early Jewish literature |editor=Michael E. Stone |editor2=Theodore E. Bergren |title=Biblical Figures Outside the Bible |publisher=Trinity Press |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eXM1YwCGipMC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |year=2001 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Freedman |first=Paul H. |title=Images of the Medieval Peasant |year=1999 |publisher=Stanford University Press |isbn= 9780804733731|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RXBReIaQDW8C#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Goldenberg |first=David M. |editor1-last=Stemberger |editor1-first=G\u00fcnter |editor2-last=Perani |editor2-first=Mauro |title=The Words of a Wise Man's Mouth are gracious |chapter=What did Ham do to Noah? |year=2005 |pages= |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn= |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4cr-mix9kMgC&pg=PA261#v=onepage&q=curse%20of%20ham%20greek%20mesopotamian%20myth&f=false |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Goldenberg |first1=David M. |year=2003 |title=The Curse of Ham: Race and Slavery in Early Judaism, Christianity, and Islam |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=9780691114651 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QFHB2D4XH8UC |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Goldenberg |first=David M. |editor1-last=Salzman |editor1-first=Jack |editor2-last=West |editor2-first=Cornel |title=Struggles in the promised land: toward a history of Black-Jewish relations |chapter=The Curse of Ham: A Case of Rabbinic Racism? |year=1997 |pages= |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780198024927 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C2MJkRjpOHoC&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q=%22long%20history%20of%20enslaving%22&f=false |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Goldenberg |first1=David M. |title=The Curse of Ham: Race and Slavery in Early Judaism, Christianity, and Islam |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=9781400828548 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1MS9AiZ74MoC&pg=PA168#v=onepage&q=%22skin%20color%20and%20slavery%22&f=false |year=2009 |ref=harv }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Graves |first1=Robert |last2=Patai |first2=Raphael |title=Hebrew Myths: The Book of Genesis |publisher=Princeton University Press, Cassel |year=1964 |isbn= |url= |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web |last1=Ham |first1=Ken |authorlink1=Ken Ham |last2=Sarfati |first2=Jonathan |authorlink2=Jonathan Sarfati |last3=Wieland |first3=Carl |authorlink3=Carl Wieland |year=2001 |editor-last=Batten |editor-first=Don |url=http://www.christiananswers.net/q-aig/race-blacks.html |title=Are Black People the Result of a Curse on Ham |website=ChristianAnswers.net |accessdate=28 September 2013 |quote= |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Keil |first1=Carl |last2=Delitzsch |first2=Franz |others=Trans. James Martin |title=Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament |volume=1 |year=1885 |publisher=T&T Clark |location=Edinburgh |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kissling |first=Paul |title=Genesis |publisher=College Press |year=2004 |volume=volume 1 |isbn= 9780899008752|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lotBnvqdmeQC&pg=PP4#v=onepage&q=In%20the%20beginning&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Kugle |first=James L. |title=Traditions of the Bible |publisher=Harvard University Press |year=1998 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QUkaVq_GlJUC&pg=PA222#v=onepage&q=%22Ham%20laughed%22&f=false |ref=harv|isbn=9780674791510 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Levenson |first=Jon D. |editor1-last=Berlin |editor1-first=Adele |editor2-last=Brettler |editor2-first=Marc Zvi |title=The Jewish study Bible |chapter=Genesis: Introduction and Annotations |year=2004 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195297515/page/26 26] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-529751-5 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aDuy3p5QvEYC#v=onepage&q&f=false |ref=harv |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195297515/page/26 }} ([https://books.google.com/books?id=aDuy3p5QvEYC&pg=PR5#v=snippet&q=Levenson&f=false Levenson author note]).\n*{{cite book |last=Lulat |first=G |title=A History of African Higher Education from Antiquity to the Present: A Critical Synthesis. |year=2005 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |location=Santa Barbara |isbn=9780313068669 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J00xEkY-vTEC&pg=PA86#v=onepage&q=misnomer%20ham&f=false |pages=85, 86 |ref=harv |quote=an ideologically driven misnomer...}}\n*{{cite book |last=Metcalf |first=Alida C. |title=Go-betweens and the Colonization of Brazil, 1500\u20131600 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lWuNIISvBqIC#v=snippet&q=ham%20curse&f=false |year=2005 |publisher=[[University of Texas Press]] |location=Austin |isbn=978-0292712768 |edition=1st |page=164 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Reeve|first1=W. Paul|title=Religion of a Different Color: Race and the Mormon Struggle for Whiteness|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=95j4BQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|location=New York, New York|isbn=978-0-19-975407-6}}\n*{{cite book |last=Robertson |first=John M. |authorlink= |title=Christianity and Mythology |year=1910 |publisher=Kessinger Publishing (2004 reprint) |location= |isbn=978-0-7661-8768-9 |pages=496 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=usGxKc9gMNwC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sadler |first=R.S. |authorlink= |title=Can a Cushite Change his Skin? |year=2005 |publisher=T&T Clark |location= |language= |isbn= 9780567029607|pages=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jNwI0AlRhuwC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sarna |first=Nahum |authorlink=Nahum Sarna |editor-last=Friedman |editor-first=Richard Elliott |title=The Creation of Sacred Literature: Composition and Redaction of the Biblical Text |chapter=The Anticipatory Use of Information as a Literary Feature of the Genesis Narratives |year=1981 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-09637-0 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HvjNTNWTyQUC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/creationofsacred0000unse }}\n*{{Cite book |last=Trost |first=Travis D. |title=Who should be king in Israel? |publisher=Peter Lang Publishing |year=2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FnvbpnRwxeYC&pg=PR6#v=onepage&q&f=false |ref=harv|isbn=9781433111518 }}\n*{{cite book |last=VanderKam |first=James Claire |authorlink=James VanderKam |chapter=The Righteousness of Noah |editor=John Joseph Collins |editor2=George W. E. Nickelsburg |title=Ideal figures in ancient Judaism: profiles and paradigms, Volumes 12\u201315 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Le4QAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=1 December 2013 |year=1980 |publisher=Scholars Press |location=Chico |isbn=978-0891304340 |pages=13\u201332|ref=harv}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150309230136/http://www3.nd.edu/~jvanderk/ VanderKam-Vitae]\n*{{cite book |last=Van Seters |first=John |editor1-last=VanderKam |editor1-first=James |title=From Revelation to Canon: Studies in the Hebrew Bible and Second Temple Literature |chapter=Geography as an evaluative tool |year=2000 |pages=|publisher=Brill |isbn= |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L352z_jZSmcC&pg=PA476#v=onepage&q=Putting%20them%20in%20their%20place%3A%20Geography%20as%20an%20evaluative%20tool&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Whitford |first=David M. |title=The curse of Ham in the Early Modern Era |publisher=Ashgate Publishing |year=2009 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hMb7_SL-OJYC#v=onepage&q=&f=false |ref=harv|isbn=9780754666257 }}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Noah (Biblical figure)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/11571-noah \"Noah\"] from the 1901\u20131906 ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]''\n*[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11088a.htm \"Noah\"]\u2014''[[Catholic Encyclopedia]]''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090711130618/http://muslimwiki.com/mw/index.php/Nuh \"Nuh\"]\u2014MuslimWiki\n\n{{Prophets of the Tanakh}}\n{{Adam to David}}\n{{Prophets in the Qur'an|no}}\n{{Noah's Ark}}\n{{Creationism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Noah| ]]\n[[Category:Bereshit (parsha)]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the Old Testament]]\n[[Category:Legendary progenitors]]\n[[Category:Longevity myths]]\n[[Category:Noach (parsha)| ]]\n[[Category:People celebrated in the Lutheran liturgical calendar]]\n[[Category:Book of Genesis people]]\n", "name_user": "98.209.103.172", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noah"}
{"title_page": "The King's University (Edmonton)", "text_new": "{{For|other similar names|King's College (disambiguation)|King's University (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = The King's University\n| image = The King's University Edmonton, Alberta, Canada logo.png\n| motto = \"Teaching Each Other in All Wisdom\"\n| president = Melanie J. Humphreys\n| type = [[Universities|liberal arts college]]\n| affiliation = [[Christian Reformed Church in North America]]\n| established = 1979\n| city = [[Edmonton]]\n| province = [[Alberta]]\n| country = Canada\n| students = 910\n| endowment = CA$1,863,967<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/administrative-departments/financial-services/financial-statements|title=Archived Financial Statements|website=Kingsu.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n| faculty = 120\n| campus = Urban, {{convert|20|acre|ha|2|abbr=on}}\n| colors = Blue, Teal, Navy Blue, Bright Blue, Gold {{color box|#0078BF}} {{color box|#40AAB8}} {{color box|#003B5C}} {{color box|#0078BF}} {{color box|#F1B434}}\n| mascot = Eagle\n| website = http://www.kingsu.ca/\n}}\n\n'''The King's University''' located in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], [[Canada]], is a private Canadian Christian university offering bachelor's degrees in the arts, humanities, music, social sciences, natural sciences and business, and education. King\u2019s currently serves more than 900 students from across Canada and abroad, representing more than 16 nations.\n\n==History==\nOn November 16, 1979, the Alberta Legislature approved The King's College Act which granted a charter to The King's College. King's was founded, by the Christian College Association (Alberta) as The King's College.\n\nIn December 1970, a constitution, and statement of principles gave written expression to their vision of Christian Higher education. King's is a member of the [[Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]]. The enabling legislation is the ''Post-secondary Learning Act''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qp.alberta.ca/574.cfm?page=p19p5.cfm&leg_type=Acts&isbncln=9780779737932|title=Alberta Queen's Printer:|first=Government of|last=Alberta|date=17 September 2012|website=Qp.alberta.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 1983, an official affiliation agreement was signed with the University of Alberta, ensuring that the great majority of courses at King's would transfer automatically to the University and making various University resources, such as the library and curriculum labs, available to college students. In 1987, The King's College was given the right to grant its first accredited degree, a three-year B.A., with concentrations in a number of disciplines. Since then, it has been authorized to offer many other degree programs, as listed in this calendar.\n\nIn the summer of 1993, the College moved into its first permanent campus. In November of that year, the Alberta legislature approved the bill changing the College's name to The King's University College.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.assembly.ab.ca/ISYS/LADDAR_files/docs/bills/bill/legislature_23/session_1/19930830_bill-Pr010.pdf|format=PDF|title=Bill PR10 : THE KING'S COLLEGE AMENDMENT ACT, 1993|website=Assembly.ab.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> In November 2015, the Alberta legislature passed a private member's bill changing the name to \"The King's University\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=Pr001&legl=29&session=1|title=Bills and Amendments- Legislative Assembly of Alberta|website=Assembly.ab.ca|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\nKing's partners with other Canadian organizations to provide education opportunities to students. Most notably, in 2011 The King\u2019s Environmental Studies (ENVS) Program was granted professional accreditation from Environmental Careers Organization [[ECO Canada]], the certifying body of the Canadian Environmental Accreditation Commission (CEAC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eco.ca/program-accreditation/|title=Accreditation - ECO Canada|website=Eco.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> In 2013 King\u2019s signed an agreement with [[Newman Theological College]] to offer Bachelor of Education students the religious education courses necessary to be eligible for a continuous contract with [[Edmonton Catholic School District]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kingsu.ca/news/post/4690 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213221956/http://www.kingsu.ca/news/post/4690 |archivedate=2013-12-13 }}</ref>\n \nIn 2013, King's inaugurated  fourth President Dr. Melanie J. Humphreys. Dr. Humphreys took office on July 2, 2013 after the retirement of President Emeritus Dr. J Harry Fernhout (2005-2013). Dr. Fernhout was preceded by Dr. Henk Van Andel (1985- 2005) and founding President Dr. Sidney DeWaal (1979-1983).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/history |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112234721/http://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/history |archivedate=2013-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n===Equal-rights case===\nIn the early 1990s, The King's University drew attention due to a controversial decision to fire an employee ([[Delwin Vriend]], a lab assistant) because he was gay. Since the Alberta Individual Rights Protection Act did not cover discrimination based on sexual orientation, the Human Rights Commission did not want to investigate it. The employee, however, took his case to court, which decided in 1994 that sexual orientation should be added to the act, a decision appealed by the government and overturned in 1996. But [[Vriend v. Alberta]], brought before the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] in 1997 and decided in 1998, with the unanimous decision that \"the exclusion of homosexuals from Alberta's Individual Rights Protection Act is a violation of the Charter of Rights and Freedoms\".<ref>{{cite news|last=|title=Timeline: Same Sex Rights in Canada|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2012/01/12/f-same-sex-rights.html|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Programs==\nStudents can enroll in over 650 courses across 37 disciplines, with 17 major concentration areas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/about-kings|title=About King's|website=www.kingsu.ca|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\nThe King's University offers three-year and four-year bachelor's degrees in the arts, humanities, social sciences, natural sciences, and commerce, as well as a two-year Bachelor of Education after-degree. Prominent programs include the [https://www.kingsu.ca/programs/bachelor/environmental-studies Environmental Studies program] and the [https://www.kingsu.ca/programs/bachelor/politics-history-economics Politics-History-Economics] (PHE) combined major. Currently the university has over 900 students<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/about-kings|title=About King's|website=www.kingsu.ca|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref> enrolled in Bachelor of Arts, Bachelor of Science, Bachelor of Music, Bachelor of Commerce and Bachelor of Education programs. The King's University accepts academically qualified students of all faiths into its programs.\n\n==Research==\nTraining of undergraduates in laboratory, field, or literary research, is figured prominently at King's. Many projects are collaborative with other universities, non-government organizations, community groups, or international partnerships. The King's Centre for Visualization in Science <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcvs.ca|title=The King's Centre for Visualization|website=Kcvs.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> is developing computer-based teaching tools for high school science teachers to simulate properties and processes in chemistry and physics . Research with implications for social policy include Alberta's oil sands, pluriformity in Alberta's public education system and national delivery of men's health services. Sustainability in business, communities, and resource-based livelihoods in Africa is the research focus of international partnerships with non-government organizations and other universities.<ref name=\"aucc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aucc.ca/can_uni/our_universities/kings_ab_e.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-04-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411025126/http://www.aucc.ca/can_uni/our_universities/kings_ab_e.html |archivedate=2008-04-11 }}</ref>\n\n== The Simona Maaskant Library ==\n[[File:SimonaMaaskantLibrary.jpg|thumb|Exterior view of the Simona Maaskant Library]]\nThe King's University library was renamed the Simona Maaskant Library in 1998, named after its chief librarian Simona Maaskant.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Janson|first=Marlies|title=World Guide to Special Libraries|last2=Optiz|first2=Helmut|publisher=De Gruyter|year=2011|isbn=9783110917857|volume=1|location=|pages=422}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/476073016/|title=Maaskant, Simona Margaretha|date=April 29, 1998|work=The Edmonton Journal|access-date=|url-status=live|page=B6}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/services/library/about-simona-maaskant-library|title=About the Library|website=www.kingsu.ca|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The Simona Maaskant Library contains over 75,000 physical materials (books and audiovisual materials) and 200,000 electronic materials.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe library is a member of the [[NEOS Library Consortium]] therefore offering users access to an additional 10 million materials through the consortium.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThe Simona Maaskant Library also includes a special collections and archives division called The Gerry Segger Heritage Collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebanner.org/news/2015/03/preserving-stories-of-the-dutch-canadian-immigrant-experience|title=Preserving Stories of the Dutch-Canadian Immigrant Experience|website=The Banner|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> The collection acts as a research centre for archival materials associated with [[Dutch Canadians|Dutch-Canadians]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christiancourier.ca/news/entry/saving-dutch-canadian-history|title=Saving Dutch-Canadian History|last=Bruinsma|first=Robert|date=May 25, 2019|website=www.christiancourier.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==The Micah Centre==\nThe Micah Centre is focused on transformational development and social justice aims to provide students with further transformative experiences that shape their educational and vocational choices. The Micah Centre hosts the Interdisciplinary Studies Conference. A two-day conference held in the Fall and Winter semesters. Past topics include: [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission]], Economics and Christian Desire, Culture Making, and The Alberta Oilsands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingsu.ca/faculties/interdisciplinary-studies/is-conference/past-conferences|title=Past Conferences|website=Kingsu.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Micah Centre also coordinates The Honduras Water Project,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://micahcentre.ca/opportunities/honduras-water-project/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211001728/http://micahcentre.ca/opportunities/honduras-water-project/ |archive-date=2013-12-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> recipients of Alberta's Award of Distinction for Internationalizing the Teaching and Learning Practice, annually sends service-learning teams to a remote Honduran village to both learn about poverty and development firsthand, and work alongside residents in constructing a community water system. Recent Micah internships with global NGO partners have emphasized community organization (Bangladesh), HIV/AIDs (Tanzania), and environmental sustainability (Kenya).\n\n==International studies==\nKing's partners with more than 25 off-campus study programs  various locations including the [[Au Sable Institute]] of Environmental Studies (India, USA), Netherlandic Study Program, China Studies, Russia Studies, Middle East Studies, Film Studies (Los Angeles), and Uganda Studies. International students are eligible for campus employment in university research projects, the library, facility and grounds department, Tamil studies, and food services, among others.\n\n==Statistics==\n(as of  Fall 2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://registry.kingsu.ca/Stats/index.html|title=Registry Stats|website=registry.kingsu.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n*Enrollment:  910<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/about-kings|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705042900/http://www.aucc.ca/canadian-universities/our-universities/the-kings-university-college-2/|archivedate=2013-07-05|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-06-28}}</ref>\n*Student to Faculty Ratio:  9:1\n*Male to Female Ratio: 5:7\n*Number of Faculty:\t120\n*Number of Full-time Faculty:50\n\n==Rankings and distinctions==\nFor the last five years, King\u2019s has been a leader in its sector with \u201ctop of the class\u201d grades for Student-Faculty Interaction, Class Size, Quality of Teaching, and Most Satisfied Student in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' Canadian University Report.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/education/canadian-university-report/canadian-university-report-2013-student-satisfaction-survey-results/article4631980/ | location=Toronto | work=The Globe and Mail | title=Canadian University Report 2013: Student satisfaction survey results | date=23 October 2012}}</ref>  It was also named best small university in Canada by [[Maclean\u2019s]] magazine for several years running. Most recently, King\u2019s was named Most Supportive Campus Environment of any Canadian Institution, as measured by the [[National Survey of Student Engagement]], and is in the top ten per cent of all colleges and universities in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oncampus.macleans.ca/education/rankings/|title=Maclean\u2019s Education hub|website=Oncampus.macleans.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nKing's received an A+ rating for overall student satisfaction on the Globe and Mail 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011 and 2012 Canadian University Reports.  \n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globecampus.ca/navigator/kings-university-college-the/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504175350/http://www.globecampus.ca/navigator/kings-university-college-the/ |archivedate=2009-05-04 }}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n[https://athletics.kingsu.ca/landing/index The King's University Eagles], compete in the [[Alberta Colleges Athletics Conference]]. Team sports include basketball, soccer, badminton and volleyball.\n\nIn the 2008-2009 season, the women's basketball team won their first ever bronze medal.[http://www.kingsu.org/athletics/index.html]\n\n==Campus==\nKing's buildings have floor area of {{convert|21,000|m2|sqft|0}} on a site of {{convert|80,000|m2|sqft|0}}. Facilities include: 34 classrooms, eight science labs, three computer labs, a greenhouse, fine arts studios, a performance hall with pipe organ, {{convert|1,200|m2|sqft|0|abbr=on}} library, {{convert|900|m2|sqft|0|abbr=on}} gymnasium, spacious cafeteria, Students' Association center, drama space, bookstore, conference rooms, atrium assembly space, outdoor sports fields, and two student residences.[http://www.kingsu.org/about-us/history.html]\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Ronald A. Kuipers]] ('91) - Philosopher of religion at the [[Institute for Christian Studies]] in [[Toronto]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/programs/additional-academics/is-conference/past-conferences/post/glorious-and-free-generous-citizenship-for-the-next-150|title=\"Glorious and Free\"?! Generous Citizenship for the Next 150|website=www.kingsu.ca|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n*William Choy ('95, '97)- Mayor of the Town of [[Stony Plain, Alberta]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stonyplain.com/Town-Hall/Mayor-and-Council/Mayor-s-Office.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021205815/http://www.stonyplain.com/Town-Hall/Mayor-and-Council/Mayor-s-Office.htm |archive-date=2013-10-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Ann Vriend]] ('97) - Winner of the [[Ottawa Bluesfest]]'s 2013 'She's the One' contest for emerging artists\n*Dr. Harold Jansen ('97) - Board of Governors Teaching Chair at [[University of Lethbridge]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uleth.ca/notice/display.html?b=300&s=19347 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210033423/http://www.uleth.ca/notice/display.html?b=300&s=19347 |archivedate=2013-12-10 }}</ref>\n*Dr. Kristopher J. Ooms ('01) - Professor of Chemistry, in the field of [[NMR spectroscopy]]\n\n==Notable faculty==\n*Dr. Peter Mahaffy - (2006\u20132009) Chair of the [[International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry]] (IUPAC) Committee on Chemistry Education.\n*Dr. [[Jacobus Kloppers]] (Professor Emeritus) - Internationally known classical organist.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kingsu.ca The King's University]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110706183954/http://www.kingsu.ca/library/index.html The King's University library]\n{{Ab Uni|college=yes|private=yes|technical=yes}}\n{{CCCU}}\n\n{{Coord|display=title|53|31|31|N|113|25|3|W|region:CA-AB_type:landmark}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King's University, The}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Nondenominational Christian universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1979]]\n[[Category:Evangelicalism in Canada]]\n[[Category:1979 establishments in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]]\n[[Category:Higher education in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other similar names|King's College (disambiguation)|King's University (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = The King's University\n| image = The King's University Edmonton, Alberta, Canada logo.png\n| motto = \"Teaching Each Other in All Wisdom\"\n| president = Melanie J. Humphreys\n| type = [[Universities|liberal arts college]]\n| affiliation = [[Christian Reformed Church in North America]]\n| established = 1979\n| city = [[Edmonton]]\n| province = [[Alberta]]\n| country = Canada\n| students = 910\n| endowment = CA$1,863,967<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/administrative-departments/financial-services/financial-statements|title=Archived Financial Statements|website=Kingsu.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n| faculty = 120\n| campus = Urban, {{convert|20|acre|ha|2|abbr=on}}\n| colors = Blue, Teal, Navy Blue, Bright Blue, Gold {{color box|#0078BF}} {{color box|#40AAB8}} {{color box|#003B5C}} {{color box|#0078BF}} {{color box|#F1B434}}\n| mascot = Eagle\n| website = http://www.kingsu.ca/\n}}\n\n'''The King's University''' located in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], [[Canada]], is a private Canadian Christian university offering bachelor's degrees in the arts, humanities, music, social sciences, natural sciences and business, and education. King\u2019s currently serves more than 900 students from across Canada and abroad, representing more than 16 nations.\n\n==History==\nOn November 16, 1979, the Alberta Legislature approved The King's College Act which granted a charter to The King's College. King's was founded, by the Christian College Association (Alberta) as The King's College.\n\nIn December 1970, a constitution, and statement of principles gave written expression to their vision of Christian Higher education. King's is a member of the [[Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]]. The enabling legislation is the ''Post-secondary Learning Act''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qp.alberta.ca/574.cfm?page=p19p5.cfm&leg_type=Acts&isbncln=9780779737932|title=Alberta Queen's Printer:|first=Government of|last=Alberta|date=17 September 2012|website=Qp.alberta.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 1983, an official affiliation agreement was signed with the University of Alberta, ensuring that the great majority of courses at King's would transfer automatically to the University and making various University resources, such as the library and curriculum labs, available to college students. In 1987, The King's College was given the right to grant its first accredited degree, a three-year B.A., with concentrations in a number of disciplines. Since then, it has been authorized to offer many other degree programs, as listed in this calendar.\n\nIn the summer of 1993, the College moved into its first permanent campus. In November of that year, the Alberta legislature approved the bill changing the College's name to The King's University College.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.assembly.ab.ca/ISYS/LADDAR_files/docs/bills/bill/legislature_23/session_1/19930830_bill-Pr010.pdf|format=PDF|title=Bill PR10 : THE KING'S COLLEGE AMENDMENT ACT, 1993|website=Assembly.ab.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> In November 2015, the Alberta legislature passed a private member's bill changing the name to \"The King's University\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=bills_status&selectbill=Pr001&legl=29&session=1|title=Bills and Amendments- Legislative Assembly of Alberta|website=Assembly.ab.ca|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\nKing's partners with other Canadian organizations to provide education opportunities to students. Most notably, in 2011 The King\u2019s Environmental Studies (ENVS) Program was granted professional accreditation from Environmental Careers Organization [[ECO Canada]], the certifying body of the Canadian Environmental Accreditation Commission (CEAC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eco.ca/program-accreditation/|title=Accreditation - ECO Canada|website=Eco.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> In 2013 King\u2019s signed an agreement with [[Newman Theological College]] to offer Bachelor of Education students the religious education courses necessary to be eligible for a continuous contract with [[Edmonton Catholic School District]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kingsu.ca/news/post/4690 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213221956/http://www.kingsu.ca/news/post/4690 |archivedate=2013-12-13 }}</ref>\n \nIn 2013, King's inaugurated  fourth President Dr. Melanie J. Humphreys. Dr. Humphreys took office on July 2, 2013 after the retirement of President Emeritus Dr. J Harry Fernhout (2005-2013). Dr. Fernhout was preceded by Dr. Henk Van Andel (1985- 2005) and founding President Dr. Sidney DeWaal (1979-1983).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/history |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112234721/http://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/history |archivedate=2013-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n===Equal-rights case===\nIn the early 1990s, The King's University drew attention due to a controversial decision to fire an employee ([[Delwin Vriend]], a lab assistant) because he was gay. Since the Alberta Individual Rights Protection Act did not cover discrimination based on sexual orientation, the Human Rights Commission did not want to investigate it. The employee, however, took his case to court, which decided in 1994 that sexual orientation should be added to the act, a decision appealed by the government and overturned in 1996. But [[Vriend v. Alberta]], brought before the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] in 1997 and decided in 1998, with the unanimous decision that \"the exclusion of homosexuals from Alberta's Individual Rights Protection Act is a violation of the Charter of Rights and Freedoms\".<ref>{{cite news|last=|title=Timeline: Same Sex Rights in Canada|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2012/01/12/f-same-sex-rights.html|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Programs==\nStudents can enroll in over 650 courses across 37 disciplines, with 17 major concentration areas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/about-kings|title=About King's|website=www.kingsu.ca|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref>\nThe King's University offers three-year and four-year bachelor's degrees in the arts, humanities, social sciences, natural sciences, and commerce, as well as a two-year Bachelor of Education after-degree. Prominent programs include the [https://www.kingsu.ca/programs/bachelor/environmental-studies Environmental Studies program] and the [https://www.kingsu.ca/programs/bachelor/politics-history-economics Politics-History-Economics] (PHE) combined major. Currently the university has over 900 students<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/about-kings|title=About King's|website=www.kingsu.ca|access-date=2019-07-22}}</ref> enrolled in Bachelor of Arts, Bachelor of Science, Bachelor of Music, Bachelor of Commerce and Bachelor of Education programs. The King's University accepts academically qualified students of all faiths into its programs.\n\n==Research==\nTraining of undergraduates in laboratory, field, or literary research, is figured prominently at King's. Many projects are collaborative with other universities, non-government organizations, community groups, or international partnerships. The King's Centre for Visualization in Science <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcvs.ca|title=The King's Centre for Visualization|website=Kcvs.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref> is developing computer-based teaching tools for high school science teachers to simulate properties and processes in chemistry and physics . Research with implications for social policy include Alberta's oil sands, pluriformity in Alberta's public education system and national delivery of men's health services. Sustainability in business, communities, and resource-based livelihoods in Africa is the research focus of international partnerships with non-government organizations and other universities.<ref name=\"aucc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aucc.ca/can_uni/our_universities/kings_ab_e.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-04-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411025126/http://www.aucc.ca/can_uni/our_universities/kings_ab_e.html |archivedate=2008-04-11 }}</ref>\n\n== The Simona Maaskant Library ==\n[[File:SimonaMaaskantLibrary.jpg|thumb|Exterior view of the Simona Maaskant Library]]\nThe King's University library was renamed the Simona Maaskant Library in 1998, named after its chief librarian Simona Maaskant.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Janson|first=Marlies|title=World Guide to Special Libraries|last2=Optiz|first2=Helmut|publisher=De Gruyter|year=2011|isbn=9783110917857|volume=1|location=|pages=422}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/476073016/|title=Maaskant, Simona Margaretha|date=April 29, 1998|work=The Edmonton Journal|access-date=|url-status=live|page=B6}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/services/library/about-simona-maaskant-library|title=About the Library|website=www.kingsu.ca|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The Simona Maaskant Library contains over 75,000 physical materials (books and audiovisual materials) and 200,000 electronic aid materials.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe library is a member of the [[NEOS Library Consortium]] therefore offering users access to an additional 10 million materials through the consortium.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThe Simona Maaskant Library also includes a special collections and archives division called The Gerry Segger Heritage Collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebanner.org/news/2015/03/preserving-stories-of-the-dutch-canadian-immigrant-experience|title=Preserving Stories of the Dutch-Canadian Immigrant Experience|website=The Banner|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> The collection acts as a research centre for archival materials associated with [[Dutch Canadians|Dutch-Canadians]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christiancourier.ca/news/entry/saving-dutch-canadian-history|title=Saving Dutch-Canadian History|last=Bruinsma|first=Robert|date=May 25, 2019|website=www.christiancourier.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==The Micah Centre==\nThe Micah Centre is focused on transformational development and social justice aims to provide students with further transformative experiences that shape their educational and vocational choices. The Micah Centre hosts the Interdisciplinary Studies Conference. A two-day conference held in the Fall and Winter semesters. Past topics include: [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission]], Economics and Christian Desire, Culture Making, and The Alberta Oilsands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingsu.ca/faculties/interdisciplinary-studies/is-conference/past-conferences|title=Past Conferences|website=Kingsu.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Micah Centre also coordinates The Honduras Water Project,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://micahcentre.ca/opportunities/honduras-water-project/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211001728/http://micahcentre.ca/opportunities/honduras-water-project/ |archive-date=2013-12-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> recipients of Alberta's Award of Distinction for Internationalizing the Teaching and Learning Practice, annually sends service-learning teams to a remote Honduran village to both learn about poverty and development firsthand, and work alongside residents in constructing a community water system. Recent Micah internships with global NGO partners have emphasized community organization (Bangladesh), HIV/AIDs (Tanzania), and environmental sustainability (Kenya).\n\n==International studies==\nKing's partners with more than 25 off-campus study programs  various locations including the [[Au Sable Institute]] of Environmental Studies (India, USA), Netherlandic Study Program, China Studies, Russia Studies, Middle East Studies, Film Studies (Los Angeles), and Uganda Studies. International students are eligible for campus employment in university research projects, the library, facility and grounds department, Tamil studies, and food services, among others.\n\n==Statistics==\n(as of  Fall 2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://registry.kingsu.ca/Stats/index.html|title=Registry Stats|website=registry.kingsu.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n*Enrollment:  910<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/about-us/about-kings|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705042900/http://www.aucc.ca/canadian-universities/our-universities/the-kings-university-college-2/|archivedate=2013-07-05|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-06-28}}</ref>\n*Student to Faculty Ratio:  9:1\n*Male to Female Ratio: 5:7\n*Number of Faculty:\t120\n*Number of Full-time Faculty:50\n\n==Rankings and distinctions==\nFor the last five years, King\u2019s has been a leader in its sector with \u201ctop of the class\u201d grades for Student-Faculty Interaction, Class Size, Quality of Teaching, and Most Satisfied Student in ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' Canadian University Report.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/education/canadian-university-report/canadian-university-report-2013-student-satisfaction-survey-results/article4631980/ | location=Toronto | work=The Globe and Mail | title=Canadian University Report 2013: Student satisfaction survey results | date=23 October 2012}}</ref>  It was also named best small university in Canada by [[Maclean\u2019s]] magazine for several years running. Most recently, King\u2019s was named Most Supportive Campus Environment of any Canadian Institution, as measured by the [[National Survey of Student Engagement]], and is in the top ten per cent of all colleges and universities in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oncampus.macleans.ca/education/rankings/|title=Maclean\u2019s Education hub|website=Oncampus.macleans.ca|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nKing's received an A+ rating for overall student satisfaction on the Globe and Mail 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011 and 2012 Canadian University Reports.  \n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globecampus.ca/navigator/kings-university-college-the/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504175350/http://www.globecampus.ca/navigator/kings-university-college-the/ |archivedate=2009-05-04 }}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n[https://athletics.kingsu.ca/landing/index The King's University Eagles], compete in the [[Alberta Colleges Athletics Conference]]. Team sports include basketball, soccer, badminton and volleyball.\n\nIn the 2008-2009 season, the women's basketball team won their first ever bronze medal.[http://www.kingsu.org/athletics/index.html]\n\n==Campus==\nKing's buildings have floor area of {{convert|21,000|m2|sqft|0}} on a site of {{convert|80,000|m2|sqft|0}}. Facilities include: 34 classrooms, eight science labs, three computer labs, a greenhouse, fine arts studios, a performance hall with pipe organ, {{convert|1,200|m2|sqft|0|abbr=on}} library, {{convert|900|m2|sqft|0|abbr=on}} gymnasium, spacious cafeteria, Students' Association center, drama space, bookstore, conference rooms, atrium assembly space, outdoor sports fields, and two student residences.[http://www.kingsu.org/about-us/history.html]\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Ronald A. Kuipers]] ('91) - Philosopher of religion at the [[Institute for Christian Studies]] in [[Toronto]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kingsu.ca/programs/additional-academics/is-conference/past-conferences/post/glorious-and-free-generous-citizenship-for-the-next-150|title=\"Glorious and Free\"?! Generous Citizenship for the Next 150|website=www.kingsu.ca|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n*William Choy ('95, '97)- Mayor of the Town of [[Stony Plain, Alberta]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stonyplain.com/Town-Hall/Mayor-and-Council/Mayor-s-Office.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021205815/http://www.stonyplain.com/Town-Hall/Mayor-and-Council/Mayor-s-Office.htm |archive-date=2013-10-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Ann Vriend]] ('97) - Winner of the [[Ottawa Bluesfest]]'s 2013 'She's the One' contest for emerging artists\n*Dr. Harold Jansen ('97) - Board of Governors Teaching Chair at [[University of Lethbridge]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uleth.ca/notice/display.html?b=300&s=19347 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210033423/http://www.uleth.ca/notice/display.html?b=300&s=19347 |archivedate=2013-12-10 }}</ref>\n*Dr. Kristopher J. Ooms ('01) - Professor of Chemistry, in the field of [[NMR spectroscopy]]\n\n==Notable faculty==\n*Dr. Peter Mahaffy - (2006\u20132009) Chair of the [[International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry]] (IUPAC) Committee on Chemistry Education.\n*Dr. [[Jacobus Kloppers]] (Professor Emeritus) - Internationally known classical organist.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kingsu.ca The King's University]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110706183954/http://www.kingsu.ca/library/index.html The King's University library]\n{{Ab Uni|college=yes|private=yes|technical=yes}}\n{{CCCU}}\n\n{{Coord|display=title|53|31|31|N|113|25|3|W|region:CA-AB_type:landmark}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King's University, The}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Nondenominational Christian universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1979]]\n[[Category:Evangelicalism in Canada]]\n[[Category:1979 establishments in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Council for Christian Colleges and Universities]]\n[[Category:Higher education in 